One of the most violent antagonists of Bacon and of the Royal Society (names which, in his mind, were evidently very closely con- nected) was Dr. Henry Stubbe; ‘the most noted person of his age that these late times have produced' says Antony Wood, who has devoted to him one os the quaintest and most amusing of his Lives⁶¹. Stubbe vas a turncoat alike in philosophy, religion, and politica and was animated by more even than the usual bitterness of his class. His diatribes against Sprat, Glanvill, the Royal Society in general, and Bacon as their philosophical father, are, however virulent, too dull and rambling to be worth transcription, but specimens of them may be found in the Legends no Histories (1670), in the Plus Ultra reduced to a Non Plus (1670), The Lord Bacon's Relation of the Sweating-Sickness (1671), and An Epistolary Discourse concerning Phlebotomy (1671).
